AFC Leopards head coach Patrick Aussems has hailed his youthful side for the hard-fought point they earned from a barren stalemate against last season’s runners up KCB at the Thika Municipal Stadium. For Aussems, Ingwe has the youngest team in the FKF-PL this season and they have a lot to learn. “I am very much satisfied with the performance of my young players because I think we have the youngest team in the league and we have a lot to learn. They (AFC Leopards) have shown that when they are focused then we can make a good difference,” Aussems said. Leopards have surprisingly made a fine start to the campaign despite losing the plank  of their squad On his part, KCB assistant coach Geoffrey Oduor was also happy to get a point terming the result as an improvement after losing 1-2 to Gor Mahia in their opening fixture. Also Read: “Definitely that is an improvement since we lost our first match and so a point has shown that we are heading towards a good direction. After today’s(Sunday) result I think it is a must that we collect maximum points in our next fixture,” Oduor said. Oduor has also shown gratification to new additions Robinson Kamura and James Mazembe who were signed from Leopards and Kariobangi Sharks respectively. “The likes of Kamura(Robinson) are adding something in the team because when you see Kamura and Mazembe with their input working together with other players then it shows you that when they gel hen we will have a solid team and very soon we will start getting better results,” Oduor concluded. The draw took Ingwe’s points tally to four  in fifth position behind Sofapaka on goal difference while Bandari top the table on six points thanks to superior goal difference to Ulinzi Stars and third placed Kakamega Homeboyz. Leopards will next clash with Gor Mahia in Wednesday’s Mashemeji derby at Kasarani stadium while KCB line up against newbies Talanta FC. Video Of The Day: Former sports CS Hassan Wario convicted over Rio games scam